This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) because it focuses on developing a dialogue system that can understand and respond to users in a multimodal context. The paper also proposes a recurrent neural network (RNN) based model to reason on videos, which is a common technique used in natural language processing (NLP) tasks. 

The paper also involves computer vision techniques, such as visual representations and attention mechanisms, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category. 

Additionally, the paper involves machine learning techniques, such as joint-modality attention and multi-step reasoning, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-categories. 

Finally, the paper involves multimodal data, such as audio, vision, and language, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.MM (Multimedia) sub-category.
